tweet: Sound recording underwater? Your mics need to be further apart. https://t.co/ixc94yH1bj
Title: How does sound going slower in water make it hard to talk to someone underwater? | Science Questions with Surprising Answers
Description: Speed of sound in air under typical conditions is about 343 meters per second, while the speed in water is about 1,480 m/s . In general, heavier materials (those with higher mass densities) have slower speeds of sound, all else being equal .  When you talk, you do so by emitting air and then sending compression waves through this air . Your lungs provide the burst of air, and your vibrating vocal cords and mouth imprint the appropriate sound waveform on the air . Sound waves have a hard time going from air into water and mostly get reflected at the air-water interface instead of being transmitted into the water .
